BehaviorSubject is a type of subject in RxJS, which is a part of the ReactiveX library for JavaScript. In Angular, a subject is a type of observable that allows values to be multicasted to many Observers.

BehaviorSubjects are useful for representing "values over time". Unlike a standard Subject, a BehaviorSubject requires an initial value and will always return the current value to new subscribers. When you subscribe to a BehaviorSubject, you will always get the most recent value that the BehaviorSubject has emitted.

Here is an example of how you might use a BehaviorSubject in Angular:
```
import { BehaviorSubject } from 'rxjs';

@Component({ ... })
export class MyComponent {
  private mySubject = new BehaviorSubject<string>('initial value');

  constructor() { }

  nextValue(value: string) {
    this.mySubject.next(value);
  }

  subscribeToMySubject() {
    this.mySubject.subscribe((value) => console.log(value));
  }
}
```
In this example, the component has a private `BehaviorSubject` called `mySubject` that is initialized with an initial value of 'initial value'. The component also has a method `nextValue` that allows you to send a new value to the subject, and a method `subscribeToMySubject` that allows you to subscribe to the subject and receive its values.

There are a few ways you can make the `mySubject` subject available to other components so they can subscribe to it. One way is to use a service to expose the subject:
```
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { BehaviorSubject } from 'rxjs';

@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'
})
export class MySubjectService {
  private mySubject = new BehaviorSubject<string>('initial value');

  nextValue(value: string) {
    this.mySubject.next(value);
  }

  getMySubject() {
    return this.mySubject;
  }
}
```
Then, in your other component, you can inject the service and use it to get the subject and subscribe to it:
